---
// ORBIT — Pluto's unusual, eccentric, inclined orbit.
// Seeded issues:
//   * inline <svg role="img"> with no accessible name  (svg-img-alt)
//   * photo missing alt                                 (image-alt)
//   * heading jumps h1 -> h3                             (heading-order)
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Pluto's Unusual Orbit" description="Pluto's eccentric, tilted orbit and its resonance with Neptune.">
  <h1>Pluto's Strange Orbit</h1>
  <p>
    Pluto's path around the Sun is unlike that of any of the eight planets. It is
    highly elliptical and steeply tilted, and for 20 years out of every 248 it is
    actually closer to the Sun than Neptune.
  </p>

  <!-- Inline SVG orbit diagram with role="img" but NO title/aria-label (svg-img-alt) -->
  <svg role="img" viewBox="0 0 400 240" width="400" style="max-width:100%;background:#0b0c1a;border-radius:8px;">
    <ellipse cx="200" cy="120" rx="150" ry="70" fill="none" stroke="#4a6cff" stroke-width="2" />
    <ellipse cx="170" cy="120" rx="185" ry="55" fill="none" stroke="#c9a24a" stroke-width="2" transform="rotate(-12 200 120)" />
    <circle cx="200" cy="120" r="10" fill="#ffcf48" />
    <circle cx="350" cy="120" r="4" fill="#4a6cff" />
    <circle cx="20" cy="95" r="3" fill="#c9a24a" />
  </svg>

  <!-- Skipped heading level: h1 above, h3 here (no h2) -->
  <h3>An eccentric path</h3>
  <p>
    Pluto's orbit has an eccentricity of about 0.25, meaning it is noticeably
    stretched. Its distance from the Sun ranges from roughly 4.4 billion km at
    its closest (perihelion) to about 7.4 billion km at its farthest (aphelion).
    Most recently, Pluto reached perihelion in 1989 and was closer to the Sun
    than Neptune from 1979 to 1999.
  </p>

  <h2>A tilted orbit</h2>
  <p>
    Pluto's orbit is tilted about 17 degrees relative to the plane in which the
    planets travel. This steep inclination, combined with the orbit's
    eccentricity, keeps Pluto well clear of Neptune even when their orbital paths
    appear to cross.
  </p>

  <h2>Locked in step with Neptune</h2>
  <p>
    Pluto and Neptune are caught in a 3:2 <em>orbital resonance</em>: Pluto
    completes two orbits of the Sun for every three that Neptune makes. This
    gravitational rhythm ensures the two worlds never come close to colliding,
    despite their crossing orbits.
  </p>

  <!-- Photo missing alt (image-alt) -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/pluto-blue-haze.jpg" width="480" class="content-img" />
    <figcaption>Sunlight scattering through Pluto's thin, layered atmospheric haze.</figcaption>
  </figure>
</Layout>
